    - name: Variables & Data Types
      icon: variable
      levels:
        - name: String Variable
          obj: 'Create a variable `greeting` with value `"Hello"`.'
          hint: 'Try: `greeting = "Hello"`'
          expl: A string is a sequence of characters enclosed in quotes. Strings can be stored inside variables.
          sol: greeting = "Hello"
          tests:
            - ''
          max: 2/1
        - name: Integer & Float
          obj: 'Create `count = 10` and `price = 19.99`.'
          hint: 'Write both assignments, one per line.'
          expl: 'Integers are whole numbers, while floats contain decimal values.'
          sol: |-
            count = 10
            price = 19.99
          tests:
            - ''
          max: 3/1
        - name: Boolean Type
          obj: 'Create `is_ready` and set it to `True`.'
          hint: 'Try: `is_ready = True`'
          expl: 'Booleans represent truth values and can only be `True` or `False`.'
          sol: is_ready = True
          tests:
            - ''
          max: 2/1
        - name: Printing Different Types
          obj: 'Create `name = "Alex"`, `age = 18`, and print both variables.'
          hint: 'Print both variables using `print()`.'
          expl: Variables can store different data types and still be printed together.
          sol: |-
            name = "Alex"
            age = 18
            print(name, age)
          tests:
            - |
              Alex 18
          max: 4/1
        - name: Variable Update
          obj: 'Create `score = 10`, then change it to `20` and print it.'
          hint: Assign a new value to the same variable.
          expl: Variables can be reassigned to hold new values.
          sol: |-
            score = 10
            score = 20
            print(score)
          tests:
            - |
              20
          max: 4/1
        - name: Type Conversion
          obj: 'Read a number, convert it using `int()`, and store it in `age`.'
          hint: 'Try: `age = int(input())`'
          expl: '`input()` always returns text. `int()` converts it into an integer.'
          sol: age = int(input())
          tests:
            - in: '25'
              exp: ''
          max: 2/1
        - name: Type Checking
          obj: 'Read an integer into `x` using `int(input())`, then print its type using `type()`.'
          hint: 'Use `print(type(x))`.'
          expl: '`type()` returns the type of a variable.'
          start: |
            x = int(input())
          sol: print(type(x))
          tests:
            - in: '5'
              exp: |
                <class 'int'>
          max: 2/1
        - name: Character Profile
          obj: "Read a player's name and age, then print `{name} is level {age}` using an f-string."
          hint: Read two inputs and use an f-string.
          expl: Variables can store multiple kinds of information and be combined into messages.
          sol: |-
            name = input()
            age = int(input())
            print(f"{name} is level {age}")
          tests:
            - in:
                - Mage
                - '12'
              exp: |
                Mage is level 12
          max: 3/1
        - name: Data Collector
          obj: 'Read a name (string), age (int), and score (int). Print the type of each variable using `type()`, then print all three values separated by ` | `.'
          sol: |-
            name = input()
            age = int(input())
            score = int(input())
            print(type(name))
            print(type(age))
            print(type(score))
            print(f"{name} | {age} | {score}")
          tests:
            - in:
                - Alice
                - '25'
                - '90'
              exp: |
                <class 'str'>
                <class 'int'>
                <class 'int'>
                Alice | 25 | 90
            - in:
                - ''
                - '-5'
                - '0'
              exp: |
                <class 'str'>
                <class 'int'>
                <class 'int'>
                 | -5 | 0
          max: 7/1
          example:
            in:
              - Alice
              - '25'
              - '90'
            out: |
              <class 'str'>
              <class 'int'>
              <class 'int'>
              Alice | 25 | 90
